question.title: Java Swing 1.6 update 23 JVM Locks using Applet

node.contents: Hi Sean, just to confirm the Work being done on AWT-0 thread is indeed being done via SwingUtilities.InvokeLater(..). The bug you found in the Sun bug database looks very interesting and very similar to what we're experiencing here but I have checked and we are running the 1.6.0_23 version of the JRE and the code was built using the same version of the JDK.

node.contents: So as you saw, you have a blocking lock where AWT 1 and 2 are waiting on the operation in AWT-0 to get the readLock on the AbstractDocument. Have you taken multiple thread dumps back to back? space them out over 10 sec. does the same result occur for those 3 threads? How long does this lock hold?

node.contents: I currently have an applet and only recently discovered a problem with it, sometimes the whole JVM locks up and becomes unresponsive including the Java console.

astNode.text: I currently have an applet and only recently discovered a problem with it, sometimes the whole JVM locks up and becomes unresponsive including the Java console.

node.contents: Any code in the Applet that I have that updates the UI is run on the event dispatch thread. When the JVM Locked I used JVisualVM to provide a Thread Dump of the JVM. I enclose the output it below. From what I can see is that there are 3 Event Queues, but more worrying is that I think there are 2 EventDispatch threads running and mutually blocking each other in a Deadly Embrace.

node.contents: The scenario in the applet is as follows, the user wishes to browse on a textfield so we launch the browse window hosted within a JInternalFrame window, the user selects the value they want and then that value is inserted into the TextField and the browse window is dismissed.

astNode.text: The scenario in the applet is as follows, the user wishes to browse on a textfield so we launch the browse window hosted within a JInternalFrame window, the user selects the value they want and then that value is inserted into the TextField and the browse window is dismissed.

node.contents: From what I can see is that thread AWT-EventQueue-2 is updating the field on the EDT and has acquired the writeLock in javax.swing.text.AbstractDocument.replace() and tries to invalidate the textfield but waits until thread AWT-EventQueue-0 releases the Treelock, however AWT-EventQueue-0 is waiting on a readlock() on the same field but wont progress until the thread AWT-EventQueue-2 releases the writelock, hence the mutual locking. What I dont understand is it appears as if there are at least 2 EDT.

What I dont understand is it appears as if there are at least 2 EDT.

node.contents: HI thanks for the very much appreciated input. I have done some further investigating on this issue so i created just a plain basic applet and attached the JVisual VM tool to it. It showed not one but 3 EDT's as before, so in this scenario it can't be the chrriis.dj.nativeswing.swtimpl classes that are adding the extra EDT's. I have logged this issue with Sun oops Oracle and they have accepted this issue as a bug (albeit low priority in their estimation). A big thanks again to everyone who left comments/replies on this issue, they are all very much appreciated.

node.contents: The Java concurrency trail explains that acess to Swing components and their models need to happen on the EDT. However, it fails to address what happens when you have multiple EDTs.

astNode.text: The Java concurrency trail explains that acess to Swing components and their models need to happen on the EDT. However, it fails to address what happens when you have multiple EDTs.

node.contents: A better phrasing of "always access swing components from the EDT" is probably: "always access swing components from exactly one EDT".

astNode.text: A better phrasing of "always access swing components from the EDT" is probably: "always access swing components from exactly one EDT".

node.contents: The chrriis.dj.nativeswing.swtimpl classes the applet is using in its JInternalFrame are creating another EDT.

astNode.text: The chrriis.dj.nativeswing.swtimpl classes the applet is using in its JInternalFrame are creating another EDT.

node.contents: The deadlock is happening when the EDT#2 (the inner frame) is updating the text field and, at the same time, EDT#0 (the applet) is attempting to repaint the same text field.

astNode.text: The deadlock is happening when the EDT#2 (the inner frame) is updating the text field and, at the same time, EDT#0 (the applet) is attempting to repaint the same text field.

node.contents: The solution is to not pass any Swing component or their models between EDTs. Instead use a BlockingQueue with the inner frame as the producer and a SwingWorker (started by the applet) as the consumer. Once the SwingWorker reads the update from the BlockingQueue, it can pass the data back to its EDT via its done method. If you need to post intermediate results, use the publish and process methods
